Asia
---
[2] Philippines
Date: Thu 16 Jan 2014
Source: TV5 InterAksyon.com [edited]
http://www.interaksyon.com/article/78820/measles-outbreak-declared-in-olongapo-city


The city government has declared a measles outbreak in view of the rising number of cases here since the start of the year [2014]. The Sangguniang Panlungsod on Wednesday [15 Jan 2014] unanimously approved a resolution declaring an outbreak of the viral infectious disease as 62 probable measles cases were reported from 1-14 Jan 2014 this year, higher than the 23 cases reported for the same period in 2013. "The declaration is indispensable to facilitate holistic and swift responsive actions to protect the health, welfare, and well-being of the people of Olongapo as well our neighbor communities," the resolution said.

Dr Jessie Manuel, hospital administrator of the James L Gordon Hospital, said patients with suspected measles cases are continuously arriving in their hospital. Manuel said there are 80 patients with suspected measles cases being treated at the hospital, with one confirmed death since 1 Jan 2014. He said at least 90 per cent of the patients with measles are below 5 years old, with the youngest at one month old. "We are giving patients strong doses of antibiotics to address complications such as pneumonia," he said. He also said that hospital staff have already identified areas in the hospitals where the patients need to be isolated.

Meanwhile, he appealed to parents to bring their children to health centers for free vaccination, as most of the patients have not yet been given vaccination. "Measles vaccination is free in health centers," he said. With the outbreak, city health workers are now conducting house-to-house vaccination and information drives to prevent the spread of measles.

--
communicated by:
