[3] Singapore (ex Philippines)
Date: Thu 16 Jan 2014
From: Poh Lian Lim, Tan Tock Seng Hospital, Singapore


A previously healthy 32 year old Filipino man presented for medical care at Tan Tock Seng Hospital (TTSH) in Singapore on 14 Jan 2014 after returning from travel in the Philippines (Luzon). He developed fever on 10 Jan 2014, followed by cough, conjunctivitis, and facial rash on 12 Jan 2014. On examination, he had classic Koplik spots and generalized morbilliform rash. He had visited friends and relatives (VFR) in the Philippines and attended several weddings from 26 Dec 2013 until 8 Jan 2014. The patient reported that a measles outbreak was ongoing in some of the locations he had visited.

The patient was admitted and managed with appropriate isolation precautions. Measles was confirmed by PCR from a nasopharyngeal swab sample on 15 Jan 2014. The patient's pregnant wife, who had also travelled and was exposed to the patient, was found to be immune to measles and rubella.

We are reporting this because of concurrent media reports of a 7 month old infant with measles onboard a flight to Auckland from the Philippines, which necessitated contact tracing. Our patient was asymptomatic during his flight, but travel and exposure history indicates he most likely acquired his infection during VFR travel in the Philippines. The incubation period of measles (7-21 days) suggests that we will need to maintain vigilance for ongoing international spread of measles as well as secondary cases among susceptible patients.

[byline: Poh-Lian Lim, Leyland Chuang, Smriti Pathak, Su Yan Yap, Prabha Krishnan-Department of Infectious Disease, Institute for Infectious Diseases & Epidemiology (IIDE); and Department of Laboratory Medicine, Tan Tock Seng Hospital, Singapore]

--
A/Prof (Adj) Poh Lian Lim, MD, MPH, FAMS
